			<p>As the United States grapples with new directions for long-running wars in Afghanistan and Iraq, the University of Central Florida has entered into a new partnership focused on global peace and security.<br />
<br />
UCF and the United States Institute of Peace (USIP) in Washington, D.C., aim to inspire a new generation of young people to join the search for creative solutions to resolve and prevent conflicts. They will work toward that goal by enhancing UCF&rsquo;s many classes that relate to peace and security; bringing together specialists and scholars from several disciplines; and encouraging expanded community conversations on these issues.<br />
<br />
In the spring, USIP will provide one of several instructors who will team teach a newly designed course in American foreign policy. The course will be led by retired Ambassador Harriet Elam-Thomas, director of UCF&rsquo;s Diplomacy Program.<br />
&nbsp;<br />
&ldquo;You cannot find this unique blend of topics and talent anywhere else,&rdquo; said John C. Bersia, special assistant to the president for Global Perspectives.<br />
&nbsp;<br />
USIP is especially well-suited to contribute to this effort. The organization emerged from a nonpartisan commission appointed by former President Jimmy Carter and House and Senate leaders. The result was The United States Institute of Peace Act, which was signed into law by former President Ronald Reagan in 1984. USIP was officially born in 1986 as an independent, nonpartisan, national institution established and funded by Congress. <br />
<br />
The organization&rsquo;s goals are to help &ldquo;prevent and resolve violent international conflicts; promote post-conflict stability and development; and increase conflict management capacity, tools, and intellectual capital worldwide.&rdquo; <br />
<br />
UCF and the surrounding community have an expanding interest in peace and security studies. Those efforts include courses in various disciplines, student organizations that focus on peace and human rights, and participation in an annual global peace film festival.<br />
<br />
Bersia, the key UCF player in securing the partnership, said USIP will help UCF become more innovative and creative in global peace and security.<br />
<br />
&ldquo;We will have better access to informative reports and analyses from USIP for use in our programs and courses, as well as in our work with community partners such as middle and high schools,&rdquo; he said. <br />
<br />
Jeffrey W. Helsing, deputy director of domestic education and training programs for USIP, said his organization has had a strong educational mandate since its founding.<br />
<br />
&ldquo;As we continue to develop cutting-edge ideas and policy analysis that contribute to understanding and managing conflict, and building peace, this partnership with the University of Central Florida enables us to make such ideas accessible and relevant for students, teachers and scholars,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;We are excited to contribute to the growing emphasis on global awareness and peace studies at UCF.&rdquo;<br />
<br />
Roger Handberg, chairman of the Political Science Department, described the partnership as a major coup for UCF and said &ldquo;it is especially important given the expanding international presence in the department&rsquo;s undergraduate and graduate programs.&rdquo;<br />
<br />
Others with a keen interest in the partnership are the sponsors of the Sibille H. Pritchard Global Peace Fellowship. The award, given each semester to a top Central Florida college or university student, is supported by the Peace Studies Fund of the Global Connections Foundation, a nonprofit organization dedicated to global awareness, understanding and education. <br />
<br />
The Fall 2009 recipient of the award is Amal Khan, a senior at UCF majoring in political science, with an emphasis on international relations. <br />
<br />
Sibille Pritchard, the fellowship&rsquo;s namesake and president of the Global Connections Foundation, said she has long wanted to see a peace studies program at UCF and that the USIP partnership &ldquo;sounds like a strong step in that direction.&rdquo;<br />
<br />
For more information on the Global Peace Fellowship or the UCF Global Perspectives Office, visit <a href="http://www.ucfglobalperspectives.org">www.ucfglobalperspectives.org</a>. For more information about USIP, visit <a href="http://www.usip.org">www.usip.org</a>.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>UCF Stands For Opportunity: </strong>The University of Central Florida is a metropolitan research university that ranks as the 3rd largest in the nation with more than 53,500 students. UCF's first classes were offered in 1968. The university offers impressive academic and research environments that power the region's economic development. UCF's culture of opportunity is driven by our diversity, Orlando environment, history of entrepreneurship and our youth, relevance and energy. For more information, visit <a href="index.html">http://news.ucf.edu</a>.<br />
&nbsp;</p>
		
	
